title --harden-home's first real boot: live-verified, one gap patched
prompt Keaton pasted a screenshot of his outside-terminal run (key generation, the harden witness going GREEN, cursor_jail_macos.rish --harden-home launching) and asked, from inside the freshly-launched hardened window: did we do it right?
think did not trust the screenshot alone -- tested live, from inside this actual window: cat ~/.ssh/config and ls ~/.gnupg both returned Operation not permitted in real time, while ~/.gitconfig stayed readable. This is the first live, first-person confirmation that --harden-home genuinely fences a running window, not just a scripted claim about a profile file.
think confirmed the dedicated jail-local keys generated outside the jail actually landed inside this repo's gitignored .ssh/ and .gnupg-rye/, and read the real GPG fingerprint directly (D31BD189C628A42743B993FE7AD8934CB185E9DA) rather than trusting the screenshot's text.
think found git was still wired to the pre-harden identity -- core.sshCommand pointed at the old .git/ssh_config_urbit (itself pointing at the now-denied real ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_urbit_*), and user.signingkey still named the real master GPG fingerprint (now also unreadable). Rewired core.sshCommand to the new jail-local SSH keys, wrote a .gnupg-rye/gpg.sh wrapper exporting GNUPGHOME (SOURCE.md Step 8c's own pattern), and set user.signingkey to the new jail-local fingerprint.
think first SSH auth retest failed with Host key verification failed -- a real, previously unnamed consequence of --harden-home: ssh needs to read ~/.ssh/known_hosts for host-key verification, and that file lives inside the same denied ~/.ssh subpath. Fixed by ssh-keyscan-ing fresh host keys for github.com and codeberg.org into a new jail-local .ssh/known_hosts_jail, wired in via UserKnownHostsFile in the same repo-local ssh config file.
think second SSH auth retest passed host-key verification cleanly, then failed at Permission denied (publickey) -- confirmed this is the expected, honest state: the new deploy keys are generated and locally correct (diffed byte-for-byte against the screenshot's printed keys) but not yet pasted into GitHub's or Codeberg's settings pages. Reported this plainly to Keaton as the one remaining step, rather than guessing at a deeper problem that is not actually there.
think verified git status shows nothing pending and git check-ignore confirms every new key-bearing file (.ssh/id_ed25519_jail_github, .ssh/known_hosts_jail, .gnupg-rye/trustdb.gpg) stays fully gitignored under the existing /.ssh/ and /.gnupg-rye/ rules -- nothing sensitive is at risk of being committed by the new wiring.
obs this turn is the honest proof-of-concept moment for the whole --harden-home effort: a live window, tested from the inside, actually cannot read the real identity it used to depend on, and the fallback (jail-local keys) is real, present, and wired -- pending only the human act of registering the public halves with both forges.
obs the known_hosts gap is a genuinely new fact, not caught by the harden witness (which only tests file-read denial/allow, not SSH's own host-key-verification behavior) -- worth folding into the guide and witness as a follow-up, not yet done this turn since the immediate priority was getting Keaton's actual push working.
file .git/ssh_config_urbit -- repointed from real ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_urbit_* to jail-local .ssh/id_ed25519_jail_*; UserKnownHostsFile added pointing at a new jail-local known_hosts_jail
file .ssh/known_hosts_jail -- new; fresh host keys for github.com and codeberg.org via ssh-keyscan, gitignored under the existing /.ssh/ rule
file .gnupg-rye/gpg.sh -- new; GNUPGHOME-exporting wrapper per SOURCE.md Step 8c's own pattern, gitignored under /.gnupg-rye/
file session-logs/20260714-081900_harden_home_live_first_boot.bron -- this log
recommend keep-going -- once Keaton pastes the two SSH public keys and the GPG public key into GitHub and Codeberg, the next action is a real end-to-end retest (ssh -T through the new config, then an actual signed commit and push) to close this thread out fully green; after that, fold the known_hosts finding into tools/cursor_jail_macos_harden_witness.rish and manual/guides/macos-ai-jail-setup.md so a future session does not rediscover it, then return to the Neth ladder.
